ce:section.ce:para:
pH-responsive FA-CβCD-MSCDs nanocarriers have been schematically shown to prove the concept of synthesis of nano-carrier, which can be used for targeted drug delivery and imaging (Fig. 1
                        ). MSCDs synthesis was carried out as previously reported [41]. The CDs were first prepared by the pyrolysis route [40]. The sol-gel reaction was then carried out to yield mesoporous silica coatings directly outside the CDs, followed by grafting 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane on MSCD surface by silanization to create amine-MSCDs. The CβCD prepared was conjugated with amine functionalized MSCDs nanoparticles and FA was finally attached to CβCD-MSCDs surface. Thus, pH-responsive FA-CβCD-MSCDs nanoconjugates with targeting and bioimaging ability were produced. UV–Vis absorption spectra of CDs (Fig. S1) show two extensive absorption bands at 277 and 332 nm, which originate from the π-π* transition of multiple polyaromatic chromophores and n-π* transition of carbonyl groups, respectively. In the emission spectra of the CDs (Fig. S2), the emission peaks shift to longer wavelengths as the excitation wavelengths increases. The surface functional groups on CDs surface were recognized using FT-IR spectroscopy. As Fig. S3 shows, the vibrational bands at 3383, 1582, and 1389 cm−1 are associated with the corresponding hydroxyl and carboxyl groups, aromatic skeletal of CC and an aromatic amine, respectively. The crystalline nature of the CDs was identified by XRD patterns. As observed in Fig. S4, the two wide diffraction peaks at 2θ = 24.5° and 43.4°, display d spacings of 0.36 and 0.21 nm, respectively, which are associated with the graphite lattice spacings of (002) and (100). This further verifies the crystalline graphite-like structure of the synthetic CDs. Raman spectra of CDs show D and G bands at 1390 and 1600 cm−1, respectively, which are characteristic of carbon-based materials (Fig. S5). CDs have a uniform diameter of 2.66 ± 0.38 nm according to the TEM image (Fig. 2
                        (A)). The hydrodynamic size was estimated as 2.6 ± 0.49 nm by DLS test (Fig. 2(B)). EDX measurements were carried out to study the chemical composition of the CDs. Three elements can be observed in the obtained spectrum (Fig. S6A): carbon (C), oxygen (O) and nitrogen (N). The surface modification of MSCD nanoparticles was identified by FT-IR spectroscopy. Fig. 3
                        (A) displays the FT-IR spectra of MSCDs, CβCD-MSCDs, and FA-CβCD-MSCDs. FT-IR spectra of MSCDs show a broadband at 3434 cm−1 corresponding to the OH stretching vibrations of hydroxyl groups on the surface of MSCDs, the bands associated with CH stretching vibrations (2925 and 2850 cm−1), SiOSi groups (1086, 795 and 454 cm−1) and the peak at 960 cm−1 attributed to Si–OH bond stretching. CβCD-MSCD conjugate characteristic peaks at 1633 and 1560 cm−1 are ascribed to the newly formed amide bond between CβCD molecules and amine-MSCDs, respectively. Four absorption peaks at 1643, 1607, 1511, and 1405 cm−1 are observed in the spectrum of FA-CβCD-MSCDs. DLS test was carried out in order to show the stability of MSCDs-NH2, CβCD-MSCDs-ETO, and FA-CβCD-MSCDs-ETO in cell medium. The hydrodynamic size of nanoparticles in DMEM has slightly increased in comparison with those in water and PBS (Table 1
                        ). This shows that MSCDs-NH2, CβCD-MSCDs-ETO, and FA-CβCD-MSCDs-ETO are stable in DMEM. The interaction between nanoparticles and the small molecules or proteins in cell medium may be responsible for the size change of nanoparticles in DMEM [53]. The narrow size distribution of FA-CβCD-MSCDs with a particle diameter of about 100 nm, which is the proper size for obtaining effective cell penetration and targeted drug delivery [40], is observed in the TEM image (Figs. 2C and D). The size measured by TEM was smaller than that obtained by DLS method since the hydrodynamic diameter of the NPs in solution is determined by DLS while TEM measures the diameter of dried nanoparticles. TGA analysis was also carried out (Fig. 3(B)). A weight loss of 16% is measured in the case of amine-MSCDs. However, after functionalization, the weight loss increases to 22 and 24% for CβCD-MSCDs and FA-CβCD-MSCDs, respectively, confirming the higher carbon contents of CβCD and FA-CβCD modified silica compared with amine-MSCDs. The difference in weight loss between CβCD-MSCDs and FA-CβCD-MSCDs with amine-MSCDs can be associated with the decomposable CβCD and FA-CβCD groups, respectively. The low angle XRD diffractogram of the MSCDs (Fig. 3(C)) shows four peaks at 2θ = 1.5°–6°, which can be indexed to (100), (110), (200) and (210) reflections of a 2D hexagonal arrangement, respectively [54]. The XRD pattern for the FA-CβCD-MSCDs (Fig. 3(C)) shows a drastic fall of diffraction peak intensities, confirming that the pore openings of MSCDs have been efficiently covered by the CβCD. EDX analysis applied to examine the presence of the FA-CβCD-MSCDs displays the distinct peaks for carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, and silicon (Fig. S6B, Supporting Information). Fluorescence spectroscopy was used to characterize the formed FA-CβCD-MSCDs-ETO hybrids. The emission spectra of the aqueous CDs solution and ETO dissolved in methanol were also registered in excitation of 280 nm for the sake of comparison. Maximum emissions are observed at 460 and 320 nm for CDs and ETO, respectively (Fig. 3(D)). In addition, Fig. 3(D) shows that the fluorescence spectra emitted from CDs covered MS are weaker than those from free CDs. This phenomenon is due to the fact that the CDs are covered by MSN. FA-CβCD-MSCDs complex shows an emission at a 320 nm and a weak emission peak at 460 nm upon ETO encapsulation (Fig. 3(D)), further confirming that ETO has been incorporated into the FA-CβCD-MSCDs.
